desc:
Based on Kwaczała’s size – a rural village of roughly 1 500–2 000 residents – it falls into the Medium population class.  
Answer: Medium

Based on Szczyrk’s status as a small resort town of roughly 4–5 000 inhabitants and comparing it to the provided benchmarks (villages and small towns in the 1–10 000-population range generally falling into Low–Medium with places around 4 000+ tipping into Medium) Osiedle Zapelenica in Szczyrk best matches the Medium class. Answer: Medium.
Based on the urban densely populated character of Brynów-Osiedle Zgrzebnioka in Katowice and by comparison with the provided benchmarks this district falls into the “Very High” population class.
Based on its status as a small predominantly rural village in Gmina Kaczory (Piła County) with an estimated population well under 1 000 residents Dziembowo falls into the “Low” category.

Based on the size of the Kłodzki district (which is on the order of 150–200 thousand inhabitants) and comparing to the benchmarks (e.g. Zamojski ~110 K→High Piotrkowski ~90 K→Medium) Wolibórz (Nowa Ruda Kłodzki) falls into the “High” class.  
Answer: High

Based on its location in Trzebnicki (a mid‐sized suburban/rural district of Dolnośląskie with a population on the order of 70–90 000 comparable to Piotrkowski which was classed “Medium”) ulica Rakowa in Wisznia Mała should likewise be classed as:  
Medium.
Based on its status as a small rural village (just a few‐hundred inhabitants on par with Bolemin or Niwiski) Opole in Gmina Parzęczew would be classified as Low.
Based on its location in a small rural gmina (Kluczewsko) of Włoszczowa county and by analogy with similarly sized Polish villages (e.g. Morawczyna → Very Low) Rączki would be classified as Very Low.
Based on its being a suburban (yet still non‐urban) locality on the outskirts of Lublin – a major regional capital – we would place its district‐level population class in the “High” category.
Based on its role as the seat of Gmina Świlcza and a population in the several‐thousand range (around 6–9 000 residents) Świlcza would fall into the “High” class.

Based on its status as a small rural village within the Dębe Wielkie commune (a total‐gmina population of ~10 000 but individual settlements typically well under 1 000 inhabitants) and by comparison to other similarly sized Polish villages (e.g. Niwiski Bolemin) Kąty Goździejewskie is best classified in the “Low” population category.
Based on its location in the small rural gmina of Glinojeck (pop. ~8 000) and the fact that Ościsłowo itself is only a few‐hundred–inhabitant village the appropriate population band is Low.
Based on its status as a small rural village in Gmina Stara Biała (Płock County) with only a few hundred inhabitants at most Trzepowo Nowe falls into the “Low” population‐size class.
Based on its size (Trnava city ≈ 65 000 inhabitants) and in line with the examples above it falls into the “Medium” population class.

Based on Bobot being a cadastral part of the city of Trenčín (i.e. an urban neighborhood with a few‐thousand inhabitants higher density than a village but smaller than a city proper) it best fits into the medium‐population category.  

Answer: Medium
Based on Bolkov’s very small municipal population (on the order of only a few‐dozen to a few‐hundred inhabitants) it falls into the “Very Low” bracket.
Based on Holasice’s status as a small rural municipality in South Moravia (Jihomoravský kraj) with well under 2 000 inhabitants it falls into the “Low” population category.

Based on the size of most Czech‐Moravian villages bearing the name “Újezd” and in particular the one using the 783 96 postal code in Olomoucký kraj (which has on the order of one to one and a half thousand inhabitants) it falls squarely into our “Medium” category. 

Answer: Medium
Based on its status as a small village‐part of Bílovec (Nový Jičín district) with well under 1 000 inhabitants (roughly 500–700 people) Výškovice u Slatiny best fits into the “Low” population class.

Based on its size (Gyömrő is a small town of roughly 15–20 000 inhabitants comparable to Baktalórántháza) it falls into the Medium class.  
Answer: Medium
Based on Söjtör’s size (roughly 1–2 thousand inhabitants) it falls into the “Medium” class.
